40|$|Based {{on social}} {{exchange}} theory, we investigate {{the impact of}} HRM investments made by two important HR actors, i. e. <b>line</b> <b>managers</b> and the HR department, on employees’ affective commitment. More specifically, we examine the independent and joint impact of three different independent variables: the <b>line</b> <b>manager’s</b> enactment of HR practices, the <b>line</b> <b>manager’s</b> relationsoriented leadership behaviour and the HR department’s service quality. We contribute to existing literature in two ways. First, we {{pay attention to the}} HRM role of <b>line</b> <b>managers,</b> a topic largely neglected in SHRM research. Second, we focus on perceived HRM rather than intended HRM, because this is seen as the driver of employees’ attitudinal and behavioural reactions. Data for this study were collected among 1363 employees (response rate 72 %), working in three different service organizations. The results of a moderated regression analysis indicate that <b>line</b> <b>managers</b> can enhance employee affective commitment by both the effective enactment of HR practices and good relations-oriented leadership behaviour. High service quality by the HR department has an additional positive effect on employees’ affective commitment. Implications for research and practice are discussed. status: publishe...|$|R
40|$|The {{purpose of}} this {{procedure}} is to provide guidance and tools for the successful performance of management walkthroughs. This procedure is intended to complement directorate-specific processes. These walkthroughs are opportunities for <b>line</b> <b>managers</b> and workers to collaborate and clarify expectations, provide/receive feedback, and make improvements. This procedure applies to SLAC <b>line</b> <b>managers</b> as defined in Chapter 33, “Management Walkthroughs”. ...|$|R
40|$|It {{has been}} argued that the quality of the {{implemented}} HRM is crucial for the success of an organization’s HRM policy rather than the intended HRM or the mere presence of HR practices, (Boxall & Macky, 2009). As one of the key implementers of HRM in today’s organizations, line managers’ effectiveness in executing HR practices is indispensible to achieve an effective HRM implementation in the organization (Purcell & Hutchinson, 2007). However, few empirical studies have focused on this issue. We want to narrow this research gap by identifying antecedents of line managers’ HRM implementation effectiveness. More specifically, we investigate whether a strong HRM system characterized by distinct, consistent and consensual messages – as described by Bowen and Ostroff (2004) – enhances line managers’ ability, motivation and opportunity to implement HR practices, and whether this will in turn improve their effectiveness in HRM implementation. We collected data from 148 <b>line</b> <b>managers</b> and 1147 non-managerial employees in 4 Belgian organizations. The distinctiveness, consistency and consensus of the HRM system, as well as the <b>line</b> <b>manager’s</b> ability, motivation and opportunity to perform HR practices are judged by the <b>line</b> <b>managers</b> in our sample. The <b>line</b> <b>manager’s</b> effectiveness in HRM implementation is assessed by the <b>line</b> <b>manager’s</b> subordinates. Preliminary results from a multilevel path model show that ability, motivation and opportunity have to be present simultaneously to positively impact on line managers’ HRM implementation effectiveness. Furthermore, the distinctiveness, consistency and consensus of the HRM system are related to the <b>line</b> <b>manager’s</b> ability, motivation and opportunity. Considering these results, we argue that appropriate attention should be paid to create strong HRM systems that can subsequently support <b>line</b> <b>managers</b> in implementing strong people management systems. status: publishe...|$|R
